rComments: I have had this professor a couple times. Her lectures are long and consist of her reading off slides. Biggest issue is her grading style, very stubborn about giving high grades. I don't feel like she wants to have a relationship with her students at all, which isn't necessarily a bad thing just doesn't feel very welcoming.

The class definitely should have been a live session due to the topic of the class, but we are stuck listening to pre-recorded lectures. Would much prefer interaction. The readings are super long and the lectures are mostly just information from the readings put on a powerpoint. I work hard for the assignments but still just get a mediocre grade.

Professor Nagra is a great professor who knows what she is talking about. Her course isn't super heavy, as there is only one essay, one final, and a few discussion groups. She seems to care about her students and always gave extensions if needed. The only thing is that she is a tough grader and it is hard, but not impossible, to get over an 80.

Prof Nagra was interesting. Not an easy grade. The topic itself is interesting. I found her a bit rude at times. She would post prerecorded slides late with zero apology (doesn't seem to care about others time). Weekly discussions were engaging but the readings themselves were quite long pages weekly plus the textbook readings.

Bad. Used lectures from last year, and was super hard to get a hold of outside of class. Only had to go to 7/10 discussion groups, and write a reflection about it, but it was incredibly difficult to get anything above an 80%. Lectures went over assigned time, and her justification was "some are shorter some are longer". Do not recommend at all.

I really enjoy Nagra as a prof. I've had her twice and each time her lectures were really clear and easy to understand. she does make group discussions a portion of your mark but it's really not that bad. I wouldn't mind having her as a prof again tbh

Her class is very interesting, she is a great professor, and I have learned lots from this class. The only issue is how she corrects assignments. It isn't too difficult to get a 75% or 80%, but anything higher than that seems impossible.

She's a nice lady - very passionate. Most of the marks are from discussion groups but they aren't so bad and make it easy to get a good mark. She is very picky on essays even though she doesn't give details on what she wants, and gives barely any feedback. Overall, it's attainable to get an A in this course if you try.
a great prof who is very passionate. do not take this class if you want to debate racism - she's not gonna do it. DGDs are mandatory but make up a good chunk of your grade and are easy to get 4/5 on.

Terrible experience . Extremely hard marker even though her explanations for assignments are poor and she does not provide any constructive criticism on papers, instead it is just criticism in a rude way. I'm an A student and she does not give out A's even if you think its your best work yet. STAY AWAY at all costs if you care about your GPA.

prof. nagra definitely took the pandemic into consideration - 30% of your grade is discussion groups but you only have to attend 6/10 - super easy to get a good mark. the paper she assigned was alright, but was a bit hard to apply theories to. she's very accommodating and explains everything well, but the lectures can get realllllyyy long

Great professor! Lectures are not that interesting but she conveys the info very well (probably the best prof I've had in terms of conveying info). Midterms are straight forward (she tells you exactly what concepts to study and compared to other classes its not heavy). Final is take-home. Answers email. Overall one of the best uottawa crim profs!

I took a class in 3rd year for theories, and although quite strict (and marking scheme remains a mystery, picky on details) if you memorise the heck out of your notes at least an 80%. She is VERY harsh on essays though, so beware.

Literally the worst prof at uOttawa. Terrible at public speaking, drags her points out even though they are self evident. She doesn't know enough to answer student questions. Keep hold of all your returned dgds and go over her grades bc you are responsible if she loses them. Just save yourself and skip her lectures altogether. Do not need textbook.

Gives the exact questions for the midterm beforehand which is nice,but this means you must know EVERY detail. Leave something small out of your answer and you will be penalized at least 1 mark. Lectures were very minorities and justice based (took both classes and many lectures were the same), so you need to be very liberal-minded to like the clas

Very kind and approachable professor. Requires you to participate for discussion groups every week and has one midterm and one take-home final. The material of this course is very interesting. Make sure to read the textbook chapters to understand each topic.
Very caring and flexible. Extremely passionate about this class. Seems a little shy though when lecturing- repeats herself a lot. Overall though, good.

she's such a gem! she wants everyone to do well so she deliberately sets her exams up accordingly (SHE LITERALLY TELLS YOU WHATS ON THE EXAM). she repeats everything so you it stays in your head. an overall sweetheart who uses a lot of examples and class discussion. please take her!
Baljit is a great prof, and a very fair marker. Lots of readings but doable. Would recommend for an upper year Crim course.
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Get ready to read', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Uses her own experiences as evidence, and uses absolutes for stats when its not so clear cut. Repeats things three times straight out of her readings, and her MC questions are easy enough to guess without studying. She is a nice person, she just lacks knowledge on the justice system (Does not know statutory release exists) which is bad for crim.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Group projects', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Her course material was very interesting so going to class and listening was not a struggle. Also, she is very social justice oriented and has very firm liberal opinions, which can be a good or bad thing depending on your own view. My main complain is that there are A LOT of readings, but the exams aren't too hard and her grading is quite fair.
